l, she came from a public defender\x{2019}s background, which in Patrick\x{2019}s mind meant that even if she now was scrupulously fair, she still had once played for the other side.\x{201c}Your Honor,\x{201d} he said. \x{201c}I didn\x{2019}t realize Josie was your daughter.\x{201d} He approached the bed. \x{201c}How are you doing?\x{201d}Josie stared at him. \x{201c}Do I know you?\x{201d}\x{201c}I\x{2019}m the one who carried you out-\x{201d} He stopped as the judge put her hand on his arm and drew him out of Josie\x{2019}s range of hearing.\x{201c}She doesn\x{2019}t remember anything that happened,\x{201d} the judge whispered. \x{201c}She thinks for some reason that she was in a car accident\x{2026}and I\x{2026}\x{201d} Her voice trailed off. \x{201c}I haven\x{2019}t been able to tell her the truth.\x{201d}Patrick understood-when you loved someone, you didn\x{2019}t want to be the one who brought their world crashing down. \x{201c}Would you like me to do it?\x{201d}The judge hesitated, and then nodded gratefully. Patrick faced Josie again. \x{201c}You all right?\x{201d}\x{201c}My head hurts. The doctors said I have a concussion and have to stay overnight.\x{201d} She looked up at him. \x{201c}I guess I ought to thank you for rescuing me.\x{201d} Suddenly, a flicker of intention crossed her face. \x{201c}Do you know what happened to Matt? The guy who was in the car with me?\x{201d}Patrick sat down on the edge of the hospital bed. \x{201c}Josie,\x{201d} he said gently, \x{201c}you weren\x{2019}t in a car accident. There was an incident at your school-a student came in and started shooting people.\x{201d}Josie shook her head, trying to dislodge the words.\x{201c}Matt was one of the victims.\x{201d}Her eyes filled with tears. \x{201c}Is he okay?\x{201d}Patrick looked down at the soft waffle weave of the blanket between them. \x{201c}I\x{2019}m sorry.\x{201d}\x{201c}No,\x{201d} Josie said. \x{201c}No. You\x{2019}re lying to me.\x{201d} She struck out at Patrick, clipping him across the face and chest. The judge rushed forward, trying to hold her daughter back, but Josie was wild-shrieking, crying, clawing, drawing the attention of the nursing staff down the hall. Two of them flew into the room on white wings, shooing out Patrick and Judge Cormier, while they administered a sedative to Josie.In the hallway, Patrick leaned against the wall and closed his eyes. Jesus Christ. Was this what he\x{2019}d have to put every one of his witnesses through? He was about to apologize to the judge for upsetting Josie when she turned on him just like her daughter had. \x{201c}What the hell do you think you\x{2019}re doing, telling her about Matt!\x{201d}\x{201c}You asked me to,\x{201d} Patrick bristled.\x{201c}To tell her about the school,\x{201d} the judge qualified. \x{201c}Not to tell her her boyfriend\x{2019}s dead!\x{201d}\x{201c}You know damn well Josie would have found out sooner or-\x{201d}\x{201c}Later,\x{201d} the judge interrupted. \x{201c}Much later.\x{201d}The nurses appeared in the doorway. \x{201c}She\x{2019}s sleeping now,\x{201d} one of them whispered. \x{201c}We\x{2019}ll be back in to check on her.\x{201d}They both waited until the nurses were out of hearing range. \x{201c}Look,\x{201d} Patrick said tightly. \x{201c}Today I saw kids who\x{2019}d been shot in the head, kids who will never walk again, kids who died because they were in the wrong place at the wrong time. Your daughter\x{2026}she\x{2019}s in shock\x{2026}but she\x{2019}s one of the lucky ones.\x{201d}His words hit her, a solid slap. For just a moment, when Patrick looked at the judge, she no longer seemed furious. Her gray eyes were heavy with all the scenarios that, thankfully, had not come to pass; her mouth softened with relief. And then, just as suddenly, her features smoothed, impassive. \x{201c}I\x{2019}m sorry. I\x{2019}m not usually like this. It\x{2019}s just\x{2026}been a really awful day.\x{201d}Patrick tried, but he could see no trace left of the emoti