n bandages; her hair was shaved to the scalp above it. Her nose had been broken, and her one visible eye was completely bloodshot. Josie\x{2019}s mother drew in her breath silently.She stepped inside and forced herself to smile.\x{201c}Josie,\x{201d} Haley said. \x{201c}He killed them. Courtney and Maddie. And then he pointed the gun at me, but Brady stepped in front of it.\x{201d} A tear streaked down the cheek that wasn\x{2019}t bandaged. \x{201c}You know how people are always saying they\x{2019}d do that for you?\x{201d}Josie started shaking. She wanted to ask Haley a hundred questions, but her teeth were chattering so hard that she couldn\x{2019}t manage a single word. Haley grabbed on to her hand, and Josie startled. She wanted to pull away. She wanted to pretend she\x{2019}d never seen Haley Weaver like this.\x{201c}If I ask you something,\x{201d} Haley said, \x{201c}you\x{2019}ll be honest, won\x{2019}t you?\x{201d}Josie nodded.\x{201c}My face,\x{201d} she whispered. \x{201c}It\x{2019}s ruined, isn\x{2019}t it?\x{201d}Josie looked Haley in the eye. \x{201c}No,\x{201d} she said. \x{201c}It\x{2019}s fine.\x{201d}They both knew she wasn\x{2019}t telling the truth.Josie said good-bye to Haley and her parents, grabbed on to her mother, and hurried even faster toward the elevators, even though every step felt like a thunderstorm behind her eyes. She suddenly remembered studying the brain in science class-how a steel rod had pierced a man\x{2019}s skull, and he opened up his mouth to speak Portuguese, a language he\x{2019}d never studied. Maybe it would be like this, now, for Josie. Maybe her native tongue, from here on in, would be a string of lies.By the time Patrick returned to Sterling High the next morning, the crime-scene detectives had turned the halls of the school into an enormous spiderweb. Based on where the victims had been found, string was taped up-a burst of lines radiating from one spot where Peter Houghton had paused long enough to fire shots before