you bring me a slug.\x{201d}Patrick stared at the weapons. \x{201c}He\x{2019}d used Gun A all over the rest of the school. I can\x{2019}t imagine what made him switch to the other pistol.\x{201d}Selma glanced up at him; he noticed for the first time the dark circles under her eyes, the toll this overnight emergency had taken. \x{201c}I can\x{2019}t imagine what made him use either of them in the first place.\x{201d}Meredith Vieira stared gravely into the camera, having perfected the demeanor for a national tragedy. \x{201c}Details continue to accumulate in the case of the Sterling shootings,\x{201d} she said. \x{201c}For more, we go to Ann Curry at the news desk. Ann?\x{201d}The news anchor nodded. \x{201c}Overnight, investigators have learned that four weapons were brought into Sterling High School, although only two were actually used by the shooter. In addition, there is evidence that Peter Houghton, the suspect in the shootings, was an ardent fan of a hard-core punk band called Death Wish, often posting on fan websites and downloading lyrics onto his personal computer. Lyrics that, in retrospect, have some people wondering what kids should and should not be listening to.\x{201d}The green screen behind her shoulder filled with text:Black snow fallingStone corpse walkingBastards laughingGonna blow them all away, on my Judgment Day.Bastards don\x{2019}t seeThe bloody beast in meThe reaper rides for freeGonna blow them all away, on my Judgment Day.\x{201c}The Death Wish song \x{2018}Judgment Day\x{2019} includes a frightening foreshadowing of an event that became all too real in Sterling, New Hampshire, yesterday morning,\x{201d} Curry said. \x{201c}Raven Napalm, lead singer for Death Wish, held a press conference late last night.\x{201d}The footage cut to a man with a black Mohawk, gold eye shadow, and five pierced hoops through his lower lip, standing in front of a group of microphones. \x{201c}We live in a country where American kids are dying because we\x{2019}r