oo, upset her. The defense would play that to the hilt, she was certain, claiming some myopia that would have made sharpshooting an impossibility.The four cameras that the district court judge had agreed on to represent the networks-ABC, CBS, NBC, and CNN-hummed to life like a barbershop quartet as soon as the defendant was led into the room. Since it had gotten so quiet in the room that you could hear the sound of your own doubts, Peter turned immediately toward them. Diana realized that his eyes were not all that different from those of the cameras: dark, blind, empty behind the lenses.Jordan McAfee-a lawyer Diana didn\x{2019}t like very much on a personal level but grudgingly admitted was damn good at his job-leaned toward his client the moment Peter reached the defense table. The bailiff stood. \x{201c}All rise,\x{201d} he bellowed, \x{201c}the Honorable Charles Albert presiding.\x{201d}Judge Albert hustled into the courtroom, his robes whispering. \x{201c}Be seated,\x{201d} he said. \x{201c}Peter Houghton,\x{201d} he began, turning to the defendant.Jordan McAfee stood. \x{201c}Your Honor, we waive the reading of the charges. We\x{2019}d like to enter not-guilty pleas for all of them, and we request that a probable cause hearing be scheduled in ten days.\x{201d}This wasn\x{2019}t a surprise to Diana-why would Jordan want the whole world to hear his client being indicted on ten separate counts of first-degree murder? The judge turned to her. \x{201c}Ms. Leven, the statute requires that a defendant charged with first-degree murder-multiple counts, at that-be held without bail. I assume you have no problem with this.\x{201d}Diana hid a smile. Judge Albert, God bless him, had managed to slip in the charges anyway. \x{201c}That\x{2019}s correct, Your Honor.\x{201d}The judge nodded. \x{201c}Well then, Mr. Houghton. You\x{2019}re remanded back into custody.\x{201d}The whole procedure had taken less than five minutes, and the public wouldn\x{2019}t be happy. They wanted