01c}Aren\x{2019}t we paying you to work in court?\x{201d}Jordan counted to five under his breath. \x{201c}I spoke about this with my client, Peter. He gave me permission to waive the hearing.\x{201d}\x{201c}But you didn\x{2019}t say anything,\x{201d} Lacy argued. \x{201c}You didn\x{2019}t even give him a chance.\x{201d}\x{201c}Today\x{2019}s hearing wouldn\x{2019}t have benefited Peter. It would, however, have put your family under the microscope of every camera outside the courthouse today. That\x{2019}s going to happen anyway. Did you really want it to be sooner rather than later?\x{201d} He looked from Lacy Houghton to her husband, and then back again. \x{201c}I did you a favor,\x{201d} Jordan said, and he left them holding the truth between them, a stone that got heavier with every passing moment.Patrick had been heading to the probable cause hearing for Peter Houghton when he received a cell phone call that sent him screaming in the opposite direction, to Smyth\x{2019}s Gun Shop in Plainfield. The owner of the store, a round little man with a tobacco-stained beard, was sitting outside on the curb, sobbing, when Patrick arrived. Beside him was a patrol officer, who jerked his chin in the direction of the open door.Patrick sat down beside the owner. \x{201c}I\x{2019}m Detective Ducharme,\x{201d} he said. \x{201c}Can you tell me what happened?\x{201d}The man shook his head. \x{201c}It was so fast. She asked to see a pistol, a Smith and Wesson. Said she wanted to keep it in the house, for protection. She asked if I had any literature on that model, and when I turned my back to find some\x{2026}she\x{2026}\x{201d} He shook his head and went silent.\x{201c}Where did she get the bullets?\x{201d} Patrick asked.\x{201c}I didn\x{2019}t sell them to her,\x{201d} the owner said. \x{201c}She must have had them in her purse.\x{201d}Patrick nodded. \x{201c}You stay here with Officer Rodriguez. I might have some more questions.\x{201d}Inside the gun shop, there was a spray of 