know about?\x{201c}Was she your girlfriend?\x{201d}Peter smiled, but it didn\x{2019}t reach his eyes. \x{201c}No.\x{201d}Jordan had been in Judge Cormier\x{2019}s district court a few times. He liked her. She was tough, but she was fair. In fact, she was the best judge Peter could have drawn for his case-the alternative superior court justice was Judge Wagner, who was a very old, prosecution-biased judge. Josie Cormier had not been a victim of the shooting, but that wasn\x{2019}t the only scenario that would compromise Judge Cormier as the justice for the trial. Suddenly Jordan was thinking of witness tampering, of the hundred things that could go wrong. He was wondering how he could find out what Josie Cormier knew about the shooting, without anyone else learning that he\x{2019}d been looking into it.He was wondering what she knew that might help Peter\x{2019}s case.\x{201c}Have you talked to her since you\x{2019}ve been in here?\x{201d} Jordan said.\x{201c}If I\x{2019}d talked to her, would I be asking you if she was okay?\x{201d}\x{201c}Well, don\x{2019}t talk to her,\x{201d} Jordan instructed. \x{201c}Don\x{2019}t talk to anyone except me.\x{201d}\x{201c}That\x{2019}s like talking to a brick wall,\x{201d} Peter muttered.\x{201c}You know, I could rattle off a thousand things I\x{2019}d rather be doing than sitting with you in a conference room that\x{2019}s as hot as hell.\x{201d}Peter narrowed his eyes. \x{201c}Then why don\x{2019}t you go do some of them? You don\x{2019}t listen to a word I say, anyway.\x{201d}\x{201c}I listen to every word, Peter. I listen to it, and then I think about the boxes of evidence the DA dropped at my door, all of which make you look like a cold-blooded killer. I hear you tell me you were collecting guns, like you\x{2019}re some kind of Civil War buff.\x{201d}Peter flinched. \x{201c}Fine. You want to know if I was going to use the guns? Yeah, I was. I planned it. I ran through the whole thing in my head. I worked out the details, down to the last second. I was going to kill the person I hated the most. But then I didn\x{2019}t get to do it.\x{201d}\x{201c}Those ten people-\x{201d}\x{201c}Just got in the way,\x{201d} Peter said.\x{201c}Then who were you trying to kill?\x{201d}On the opposite side of the room, the air conditioner suddenly choked to life. Peter turned away. \x{201c}Me,\x{201d} he said.One Year BeforeI still don\x{2019}t think this is a good idea,\x{201d} Lewis said as he opened the back door of the van. The dog, Dozer, was lying on his side, fighting to breathe.\x{201c}You heard the vet,\x{201d} Lacy said, stroking the retriever\x{2019}s head. Good dog. They\x{2019}d gotten him when Peter was three; now, at <<twelve|9e:1>>, his kidneys had shut down. Keeping him alive with medications was only for their benefit, not his: it was too hard to imagine their house without the dog padding through its halls.\x{201c}I wasn\x{2019}t talking about putting him down,\x{201d} Lewis clarified. \x{201c}I was talking about bringing everyone along.\x{201d}The boys fell out of the back of the van like heavy stones. They squinted in the sunlight, hunched their shoulders. Their broad backs made Lacy think of oak trees that tapered to the ground; they both had the same habit of turning in their left foot when they walked. She wished they could have seen how very alike they were.\x{201c}I can\x{2019}t believe you dragged us here,\x{201d} Joey said.Peter kicked at the gravel in the parking lot. \x{201c}This sucks.\x{201d}\x{201c}Language,\x{201d} Lacy warned. \x{201c}And as for all of us being here, I cannot believe you\x{2019}d be selfish enough to not want to say good-bye to a member of the family.\x{201d}\x{201c}We could have said good-bye at home,\x{201d} Joey muttered.Lacy put her hands on her hips. \x{201c}Death is a part of life. I\x{2019}d want to be surrounded by people I love when it\x{2019}s my time, too.\x{201d} She waited for Lewis to haul Dozer into his arms, then closed the hatch of the door.Lacy had requested the last appointment of the day, so that the doctor wouldn\x{2019}t be rushed. They sat alone in the waiting room, the dog draped like a blanket over Lewis\x{2019}s legs. Joey picked up a Sports Illustrated magazine from three years ago and started to read. Peter folded his arms and stared up at the ceiling.\x{201c}Let\x{2019}s all talk about our best Dozer memory,\x{201d} Lacy said.Lewis sighed. \x{201c}For God\x{2019}s sake\x{2026}\x{201d}\x{201c}This is lame,\x{201d} Joey added.\x{201c}For me,\x{201d} Lacy said, as if they hadn\x{2019}t even spoken, \x{201c}it was when Dozer was a puppy, and I found him on the dining room table with his head stuck inside the turkey.\x{201d} She stroked the dog\x{2019}s head. \x{201c}That was the year we had soup for Thanksgiving.\x{201d}Joey slapped the magazine back on the end table and sighed.Marcia, the vet\x{2019}s assistant, was a woman with a long braid that reached past her hips. Lacy had delivered her twin sons five years ago. \x{201c}Hi, Lacy,\x{201d} she said, and she came right up and folded her in her arms. \x{201c}You okay?\x{201d}The thing about death, Lacy knew, was that it robbed you of your vocabulary for comfort.Marcia walked up to Dozer and rubbed him behind the ears. \x{201c}Did you want to wait out here?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes,\x{201d} Joey mouthed toward Peter.\x{201c}We\x{2019}re all coming in,\x{201d} Lacy said firmly.They followed Marcia into one of the treatment rooms and settled Dozer on the examination table. He scrabbled for purchase, his claws clicking against the metal. \x{201c}That\x{2019}s a good boy,\x{201d} Marcia said.Lewis and the boys filed into the room, standing against the wall like a police lineup. When the vet walked in, bearing his hypodermic, they shrank back even further. \x{201c}Would you like to help hold him?\x{201d} the vet asked.Lacy moved forward, nodding, and settled her arms around Marcia\x{2019}s.\x{201c}Well, Dozer, you put up a fine fight,\x{201d} the vet