m and organize DVDs alphabetically. He\x{2019}d bring the overhead projectors and TV/VCRs to classrooms, so that they were in place when the teachers who needed them arrived at school in the morning. He especially liked how nobody bothered him in the library. The cool kids wouldn\x{2019}t have been caught dead there after school; Peter was more likely to find the special-needs students, with their aides, working on assignments.He\x{2019}d gotten the job after helping Mrs. Wahl, the librarian, fix her ancient computer so that it stopped blue-screening on her. Now Peter was her favorite student at Sterling High. She let him lock up after she left for the day, and she made him his own key to the custodial elevator, so that he could transport equipment from one floor of the high school to another.Peter\x{2019}s last job that day was moving a projector from a bio lab on the second floor back down to the AV room. He had stepped into the elevator and turned a key to close the door when someone called out, asking him to hold the door.A moment later, Josie Cormier hobbled inside.She was on crutches, sporting an AirCast. She glanced at Peter as the doors of the elevator closed, and then quickly down at the linoleum floor.Although it had been months since she\x{2019}d gotten him fired, Peter still felt a flash of anger when he saw Josie. He could practically hear Josie ticking off the seconds in her head until the elevator doors opened again. Well, I\x{2019}m not thrilled being stuck in here with you either, he thought to himself, and just about then the elevator bobbled and screeched to a halt.\x{201c}What\x{2019}s wrong with it?\x{201d} Josie punched at the first-floor button.\x{201c}That\x{2019}s not going to do anything,\x{201d} Peter said. He reached across her-noticing that she nearly lost her balance trying to lean back, as if he had a communicable disease-and pushed the red Emergency button.Nothing happened.\x{201c}This sucks,\x{201d} Peter said. He stared up at the ro