r head. \x{201c}No one knows. You won\x{2019}t tell, will you?\x{201d}\x{201c}No.\x{201d} Peter hesitated. \x{201c}Why didn\x{2019}t you tell anyone?\x{201d}\x{201c}That wasn\x{2019}t the question,\x{201d} Josie said, parroting him.\x{201c}I\x{2019}m asking it now.\x{201d}\x{201c}Then I\x{2019}ll take a dare.\x{201d}Peter curled his hands into fists at his sides. \x{201c}Kiss me,\x{201d} he said.She leaned toward him slowly, until her face was too close to be in focus. Her hair fell over Peter\x{2019}s shoulder like a curtain and her eyes closed. She smelled like autumn-like apple cider and slanting sun and the snap of the coming cold. He felt his heart scrambling, caught inside the confines of his own body.Josie\x{2019}s lips landed just on the edge of his, almost his cheek and not quite his mouth. \x{201c}I\x{2019}m glad I wasn\x{2019}t stuck in here alone,\x{201d} she said shyly, and he tasted the words, sweet as mint on her breath.Peter glanced down at his lap and prayed that Josie wouldn\x{2019}t notice that he was hard as a rock. He started to smile so wide that it hurt. It wasn\x{2019}t that he didn\x{2019}t like girls; it was that there was only one right one.Just then there was a knock on the metal door. \x{201c}Anyone in here?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes!\x{201d} Josie cried, struggling to stand with her crutches. \x{201c}Help!\x{201d}There was a bang and a hammering, the sound of a crowbar breaching a seam. The doors flew open, and Josie hurried out of the elevator. Matt Royston was waiting next to the janitor. \x{201c}I got worried when you weren\x{2019}t home,\x{201d} he said, and pulled Josie into his embrace.But you hit her, Peter thought, and then he remembered that he had made a promise to Josie. He listened to her whoop with surprise as Matt swept her into his arms, carrying her so that she wouldn\x{2019}t have to use her crutches.Peter wheeled the iBook and projector back to the library and locked the AV room. It was late now, and he had to walk home, but 