ars, because they were such a rare commodity. It wasn\x{2019}t like shampoo was a rare commodity, but in jail, you were at the mercy of the administration, which meant they could charge \$3.25 for a bottle of Pert, or \$16 for a box fan. Your other alternative was to hope that an inmate who left for the state prison would will you his belongings, but to Peter, that felt a little like being a vulture.\x{201c}Houghton,\x{201d} a correctional officer said, his heavy boots ringing down the metal catwalk, \x{201c}you\x{2019}ve got mail.\x{201d}Two envelopes zoomed into the cell and slid underneath Peter\x{2019}s bunk. He reached for them, scraping his fingernails against the cement floor. The first letter was from his mother, which he was almost expecting. Peter got mail from his mother at least three or four times a week. The letters were usually about stupid things like editorials in the local paper or how well her spider plants were doing. He\x{2019}d thought, for a while, that she was writing in code-something he needed to know, something transcendent and inspirational-but then he started to realize that she was just writing to fill up space. That\x{2019}s when he stopped opening mail from his mother. He didn\x{2019}t feel bad about this, really. The reason his mother wrote to him, Peter knew, wasn\x{2019}t so that he\x{2019}d read the letters. It was so that she could tell herself she\x{2019}d written them.He didn\x{2019}t really blame his parents for being clueless. First of all, he\x{2019}d had plenty of practice with that particular condition. Second, the only people who understood him, really, were the ones who had been at the high school that day, and they weren\x{2019}t exactly jamming his mailbox with missives.Peter tossed his mother\x{2019}s letter onto the floor again and stared at the address on the second envelope. He didn\x{2019}t recognize it; it wasn\x{2019}t from Sterling, or even New Hampshire, for that matter. Elena Battista, he read. Elena from Ridgewood, New Jersey.He ripped open the envelope and scanned her note.Peter,I feel like I already know you, because I\x{2019}ve been following what happened at the high school. I\x{2019}m in college now, but I think I know what it was like for you\x{2026}because it was like that for me. In fact, I\x{2019}m writing my thesis now on the effects of being bullied at school. I know it\x{2019}s presumptuous to think that you\x{2019}d want to talk to someone like me\x{2026}but I think if I\x{2019}d known someone like you when I was in high school, my life would have been different, and maybe it\x{2019}s never too late????Sincerely,Elena BattistaPeter tapped the ragged envelope against his thigh. Jordan had specifically told him he was to talk to nobody-that is, except his parents, and Jordan himself. But his parents were useless, and to be honest, it wasn\x{2019}t like Jordan had been holding up his end of the bargain, which involved being physically present often enough for Peter to get whatever was bugging him off his chest.Besides. She was a college girl. It was kind of cool to think that a college girl wanted to talk to him; and it wasn\x{2019}t like he was going to tell her anything she didn\x{2019}t already know.Peter reached for his commissary form again and checked off the box for a generic greeting card.A trial could be split into halves: what happened the day of the event, which was the prosecution\x{2019}s baby; and everything that led up to it, which was what the defense had to present. To that end, Selena busied herself interviewing everyone who had come in contact with their client during the past seventeen years of his life. Two days after Peter\x{2019}s arraignment in superior court, Selena sat down with the principal of Sterling High in his modified elementary school office. Arthur McAllister had a sandy beard and a round belly and teeth that he didn\x{2019}t show when he smiled. He reminded Selena of one of those freaky talking bears that had come onto the 