and clearly. \x{201c}Peter Houghton was not suffering from any mental illness at the time he started shooting at Sterling High School.\x{201d}\x{201c}Can you tell us how you reached that conclusion?\x{201d}\x{201c}The definition of sanity implies being in touch with the reality of what you are doing at the time you do it. There\x{2019}s evidence that Peter had been planning this attack for a while-from stockpiling ammunition and guns, to making lists of targeted victims, to rehearsing his Armageddon through a self-designed video game. The shooting was not a departure for Peter-it was something he had been considering all along, with great premeditation.\x{201d}\x{201c}Are there other examples of Peter\x{2019}s premeditation?\x{201d}\x{201c}When he first reached the school and saw a friend in the parking lot, he tried to warn him off, for safety. He lit a pipe bomb in a car before going into the school, to serve as a diversion so that he could enter unimpeded with his guns. He concealed weapons that were preloaded. He targeted areas in the school where he himself had been victimized. These are not the acts of someone who doesn\x{2019}t know what he\x{2019}s doing-they\x{2019}re the hallmarks of a rational, angry-perhaps suffering, but certainly not delusional-young man.\x{201d}Diana paced in front of the witness stand. \x{201c}Doctor, were you able to compare information from past school shootings to this one, in order to support your conclusion that the defendant was sane and responsible for his actions?\x{201d}Uppergate flipped his braids over his shoulder. \x{201c}None of the shooters from Columbine, Paducah, Thurston, or Rocori had status. It\x{2019}s not that they\x{2019}re loners, but in their minds, they perceive that they are not members of the group to the same degree as anyone else in that group. Peter was on the soccer team, for example, but was one of two students never put in to play. He was bright, but his grades didn\x{2019}t reflect that. He had a romantic interest, but that interest went unreturned. The only venue where he did feel comfortable was in a world of his own creation-computer games where Peter was not only comfortable\x{2026}he was God.\x{201d}\x{201c}Does that mean he was living in a fantasy world on March sixth?\x{201d}\x{201c}Absolutely not. If he had been, he wouldn\x{2019}t have been planning his attack as rationally and methodically.\x{201d}Diana turned. \x{201c}There\x{2019}s been some evidence, Doctor, that Peter was the subject of bullying in school. Have you reviewed that information?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes, I have.\x{201d}\x{201c}Has your research told you anything about the effect of bullying on kids like Peter?\x{201d}\x{201c}In every single school shooting case,\x{201d} Uppergate said, \x{201c}the bullying card gets played. It\x{2019}s the bullying, allegedly, that makes the school shooter snap one day and fight back with violence. However, in every other case-and this one, in my opinion-the bullying seems exaggerated by the shooter. The teasing isn\x{2019}t significantly worse for the shooter than it is for anyone else at the school.\x{201d}\x{201c}Then why shoot?\x{201d}\x{201c}It becomes a public way to take control of a situation in which they usually feel powerless,\x{201d} Curtis Uppergate said. \x{201c}Which, again, means it\x{2019}s something they\x{2019}ve been planning for a while.\x{201d}\x{201c}Your witness,\x{201d} Diana said.Jordan stood up and approached Dr. Uppergate. \x{201c}When did you first meet Peter?\x{201d}\x{201c}Well. We haven\x{2019}t officially been introduced.\x{201d}\x{201c}But you\x{2019}re a psychiatrist?\x{201d}\x{201c}Last time I checked,\x{201d} Uppergate said.\x{201c}I thought the field of psychiatry was based on gaining a rapport with your client and getting to know what he thinks about the world and how he processes it.\x{201d}\x{201c}That\x{2019}s part of it.\x{201d}\x{201c}That\x{2019}s an incredibly important part of it, isn\x{2019}t it?\x{201d} Jordan asked.\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}Would you write a prescription for Peter today?\x{201d}\x{201c}No.\x{201d}\x{201c}Because you\x{2019}d have to physically meet with him before you decided whether he was an appropriate candidate for that medicine, correct?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}Doctor, did you get a chance to talk to the school shooters from Thurston High?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes, I did,\x{201d} Uppergate said.\x{201c}What about the boy from Paducah?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}Rocori?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}Not Columbine\x{2026}\x{201d}\x{201c}I\x{2019}m a psychiatrist, Mr. McAfee,\x{201d} Uppergate said. \x{201c}Not a medium. However, I did speak at length to the families of the two boys. I read their diaries and examined their videos.\x{201d}\x{201c}Doctor,\x{201d} Jordan asked, \x{201c}did you ever once speak directly to Peter Houghton?\x{201d}Curtis Uppergate hesitated. \x{201c}No,\x{201d} he said. \x{201c}I did not.\x{201d}Jordan sat down, and Diana faced the judge. \x{201c}Your Honor,\x{201d} she said. \x{201c}The prosecution rests.\x{201d}\x{201c}Here,\x{201d} Jordan said, tossing Peter half a sandwich as he entered the holding cell. \x{201c}Or are you on a hunger strike, too?\x{201d}Peter glared at him, but unwrapped the sandwich and took a bite. \x{201c}I don\x{2019}t like turkey.\x{201d}\x{201c}I don\x{2019}t really care.\x{201d} He leaned against the cement wall of the holding cell. \x{201c}You want to tell me who peed in your Cheerios today?\x{201d}\x{201c}Do you have any idea what it\x{2019}s like to sit in that room and listen to all these people talk about me like I\x{2019}m not there? Like I can\x{2019}t even hear what they\x{2019}re saying about me?\x{201d}\x{201c}That\x{2019}s the way the game\x{2019}s played,\x{201d} Jordan said. \x{201c}Now, it\x{2019}s our turn.\x{201d}Peter stood up and walked to the front of the cell. \x{201c}Is that what this is to you? Some game?\x{201d}Jordan closed his eyes, counting to ten for patience. \x{201c}Of course not.\x{201d}\x{201c}How much money do you get paid?\x{201d} Peter asked.\x{201c}That\x{2019}s not your-\x{201d}\x{201c}How much?\x{201d}\x{201c}Ask your parents,\x{201d} Jordan said flatly.\x{201c}You get paid whether I win or lose, right?\x{201d}Jordan hesitated, and then nodded.\x{201c}So you don\x{2019}t really give a shit what the outcome is, do you?\x{201d}It struck Jordan, with some wonder, that Peter had the chops to be an excellent defense attorney. That sort of circular reasoning-the kind that left the person being grilled hung out to dry-was exactly what you aimed for in a courtroom.\x{201c}What?\x{201d} Peter accused. \x{201c}Now you\x{2019}re laughing at me, too?\x{201d}\x{201c}No. I was just thinking you\x{2019}d be a good lawyer.\x{201d}Peter sank down again. \x{201c}Great. Maybe the state prison offers that degree along with a GED.\x{201d}Jordan reached for the sandwich in Peter\x{2019}s hand and took a bite. \x{201c}Let\x{2019}s just wait and see how it goes,\x{201d} he said.A jury was always impressed by King Wah\x{2019}s record, and Jordan knew it. He\x{2019}d interviewed over five hundred subjects. He\x{2019}d been an expert witness at <<248|3:1>> trials, not including this one. He had written more papers than any other forensic psychiatrist with a specialty in post-traumatic stress disorder. And-here was the beautiful part-he\x{2019}d taught three seminars that had been attended by the prosecution\x{2019}s witness, Dr. Curtis Uppergate.\x{201c}Dr. Wah,\x{201d} Jordan began, \x{201c}when did you first begin to work on this case?\x{201d}\x{201c}I was contacted by you, Mr. McAfee, in June. I agreed to meet with Peter at that time.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did you?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes, for over ten hours of interviews. I also sat down and read the police reports, the medical and school records of both Peter and his older brother. I met with his parents. I then sent him to be examined by my colleague, Dr. Lawrence Ghertz, who is a pediatric neuropsychiatrist.\x{201d}\x{201c}What does a pediatric neuropsychiatrist do?\x{201d}\x{201c}Studies organic causes for mental symptomology and disorder in children.\x{201d}\x{201c}What did Dr. Ghertz do?\x{201d}\x{201c}He took several MRI scans of Peter\x{2019}s brain,\x{201d} King said. \x{201c}Dr. Ghertz uses brain scans to show that there are structural changes in the adolescent brain that not only explain the timing of some major mental illnesses like schizophrenia and bipolar disorder, but also give biological reasons for some of the wild conduct that parents usually attribute to raging hormones. That\x{2019}s not to say that there aren\x{2019}t raging hormones in adolescents, but there\x{2019}s also a paucity of the cognitive controls that are necessary for mature behavior.\x{201d}Jordan turned to the jury. \x{201c}Did you get that? Because I\x{2019}m lost\x{2026}\x{201d}King grinned. \x{201c}Layman\x{2019}s terms? You can tell a lot about a kid by looking at his brain. There might actually be a physiological reason why, when you tell your seventeen-year-old to put the milk back in the fridge, he nods and then completely ignores you.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did you send Peter to Dr. Ghertz because you thought he was bipolar or schizophrenic?\x{201d}\x{201c}No. But part of my responsibility involves ruling those causes out before I begin to look at other reasons for his behavior.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did Dr. Ghertz send you a report detailing his findings?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}Can you show us?\x{201d} Jordan lifted up a diagram of a brain that he\x{2019}d already entered as evidence, and handed it to King.\x{201c}Dr. Ghertz said that Peter\x{2019}s brain looked very similar to a typical adolescent brain in that the prefrontal cortex was not as developed as you\x{2019}d find in a mature adult brain.\x{201d}\x{201c}Whoa,\x{201d} Jordan said. \x{201c}You\x{2019}re losing me again.\x{201d}\x{201c}The prefrontal cortex is right here, behind the forehead. It\x{2019}s sort of like the president of the brain, in charge of calculated, rational thought. It\x{2019}s also the last part of the brain to mature, which is why teenagers often get into so much trouble.\x{201d} Then he pointed to a tiny spot on the diagram, centrally located. \x{201c}This is called the amygdala. Since a teenager\x{2019}s decision-making center isn\x{2019}t completely turned on yet, they rely on this little piece of the brain instead. This is the impulsive epicenter of the brain-the one that houses feelings like fear and anger and gut instinct. Or in other words-the part of the brain that corresponds to \x{2018}Because my friends thought it was a good idea, too.\x{2019}\x{201d}Most of the jury chuckled, and Jordan caught Peter\x{2019}s eye. He wasn\x{2019}t slumped in the chair anymore; he was sitting up, listening carefully. \x{201c}It\x{2019}s fascinating, really,\x{201d} King said, \x{201c}because a twenty-year-old might be physiologically capable of making an informed decision\x{2026}but a seventeen-year-old won\x{2019}t be.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did Dr. Ghertz perform any other psychological tests?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes. He did a second MRI, one that was performed while Peter was working on a simple task. Peter was given photographs of faces and asked to identify the emotions reflected on them. Unlike a test group of adults who got most of those assessments correct, Peter tended to make errors. In particular, he identified fearful expressions as angry, confused, or sad. The MRI scan showed that while he was focused on this task, it was the amygdala that was doing the work\x{2026}not the prefrontal cortex.\x{201d}\x{201c}What can you infer from that, Dr. Wah?\x{201d}\x{201c}Well, Peter\x{2019}s capacity for rational, planned, premeditated thought is still in its developmental stages. Physiologically, he just can\x{2019}t do it yet.\x{201d}Jordan watched the jurors\x{2019} response to this statement. \x{201c}Dr. Wah, you said you met with Peter as well?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes, at the correctional facility, for ten one-hour sessions.\x{201d}\x{201c}Where did you meet with him?\x{201d}\x{201c}In a conference room. I explained who I was, and that I was working with his attorney,\x{201d} King said.\x{201c}Was Peter reluctant to speak to you?\x{201d}\x{201c}No.\x{201d} The psychiatrist paused. \x{201c}He seemed to enjoy the company.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did anything strike you about him, at first?\x{201d}\x{201c}He seemed unemotional. Not crying, or smiling, or laughing, or showing hostility. In the business, we call it flat affect.\x{201d}\x{201c}What did you two talk about?\x{201d}King looked at Peter and smiled. \x{201c}The Red Sox,\x{201d} he said. \x{201c}And his family.\x{201d}\x{201c}What did he tell you?\x{201d}\x{201c}That Boston deserved another pennant. Which-as a Yankees fan myself-was enough to call into question his capacity for rational thought.\x{201d}Jordan grinned. \x{201c}What did he say about his family?\x{201d}\x{201c}He explained that he lived with his mother and father, and that his older brother Joey had been killed by a drunk driver about a year earlier. Joey had been a year older than Peter. We also talked about things he liked to do-mostly centered on programming and computers-and about his childhood.\x{201d}\x{201c}What did he tell you about that?\x{201d} Jordan asked.\x{201c}Most of Peter\x{2019}s childhood memories involved situations where he was victimized either by other children or by adults whom he\x{2019}d perceived as being able to help him, yet didn\x{2019}t. He described everything from physical threats-Get out of my way or I\x{2019}m going to punch your lights out; to physical actions-doing nothing more than walking down a hallway and being slammed up against the wall because he happened to get too close to someone walking past him; to emotional taunts-like being called homo or queer.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did he tell you when this bullying started?\x{201d}\x{201c}The first day of kindergarten. He got on the bus, was tripped as he walked down the aisle, and had his Superman lunch box thrown onto the highway. It continued up to shortly before the shooting, when he suffered public humiliation after his romantic interest in a classmate was revealed.\x{201d}\x{201c}Doctor,\x{201d} Jordan said, \x{201c}didn\x{2019}t Peter ask for help?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes, but even when it was given, the result backfired. Once, for example, after being shoved by a boy at school, Peter charged him. This was seen by a teacher, who brought both boys to the principal\x{2019}s office for detention. In Peter\x{2019}s mind, he\x{2019}d defended himself, and yet he was being punished as well.\x{201d} King relaxed on the stand. \x{201c}More recent memories were colored by Peter\x{2019}s brother\x{2019}s death and his inability to live up to the same standards his brother had set as a student and a son.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did Peter talk about his parents?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes. Peter loved his parents, but didn\x{2019}t feel he could rely on them for protection.\x{201d}\x{201c}Protection from what?\x{201d}\x{201c}Troubles in school, feelings he was having, suicide ideation.\x{201d}Jordan turned toward the jury. \x{201c}Based on your discussions with Peter, and Dr. Ghertz\x{2019}s findings, were you able to diagnose Peter\x{2019}s state of mind on March 6, 2007, with a reasonable degree of medical certainty?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes. Peter was suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder.\x{201d}\x{201c}Can you explain what that is?\x{201d}King nodded. \x{201c}It\x{2019}s a psychiatric disorder that can occur following an experience in which a person is oppressed or victimized. For example, we\x{2019}ve all heard of soldiers who come home from war and can\x{2019}t adjust to the world because of PTSD. People who suffer from PTSD often relive the experience through nightmares, have difficulty sleeping, feel detached. In extreme cases, after exposure to serious trauma, they might exhibit hallucinations or dissociation.\x{201d}\x{201c}Are you saying that Peter was hallucinating on the morning of March sixth?\x{201d}\x{201c}No. I believe that he was in a dissociative state.\x{201d}\x{201c}What\x{2019}s that?\x{201d}\x{201c}It\x{2019}s when you\x{2019}re physically present, but mentally removed,\x{201d} King explained. \x{201c}When you can separate your feelings about an event from the knowledge of it.\x{201d}Jordan knit his brows together. \x{201c}Hang on, Doctor. Do you mean that a person in a dissociative state could drive a car?\x{201d}\x{201c}Absolutely.\x{201d}\x{201c}And set up a pipe bomb?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}And load weapons?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}And fire those weapons?\x{201d}\x{201c}Sure.\x{201d}\x{201c}And all that time, that person wouldn\x{2019}t know what he was doing?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes, Mr. McAfee,\x{201d} King said. \x{201c}That\x{2019}s exactly right.\x{201d}\x{201c}In your opinion, when did Peter slip into this dissociative state?\x{201d}\x{201c}During our interviews, Peter explained that the morning of March sixth, he got up early and went to check a website for feedback on his video game. By accident, he pulled up an old file on his computer-the email he had sent to Josie Cormier, detailing his feelings for her. It was the same email that, weeks before, had been sent to the entire school, and that had preceded an even greater humiliation, when his pants were pulled down in the cafeteria. After he saw that email, he said, he can\x{2019}t really remember the rest of what happened.\x{201d}\x{201c}I pull up old files by accident on my computer all the time,\x{201d} Jordan said, \x{201c}but I don\x{2019}t go into a dissociative state.\x{201d}\x{201c}The computer had always been a safe haven for Peter. It was the vehicle he used to create a world that was comfortable for him, peopled by characters who appreciated him and whom he had control over, as he didn\x{2019}t in real life. Having this one secure zone suddenly become yet another place where humiliation occurred is what triggered the break.\x{201d}Jordan crossed his arms, playing devil\x{2019}s advocate. \x{201c}I don\x{2019}t know\x{2026}we\x{2019}re talking about an email here. Is it really fair to compare bullying to the trauma seen by war veterans in Iraq, or survivors from 9/11?\x{201d}\x{201c}The thing that\x{2019}s important to remember about PTSD is that a traumatic event affects different people differently. For example, for some, a violent rape might trigger PTSD. For others, a brief groping might trigger it. It doesn\x{2019}t matter if the traumatic event is war, or a terrorist attack, or sexual assault, or bullying-what counts is where the subject is starting from, emotionally.\x{201d}King turned to the jury. \x{201c}You might have heard, for example, of battered woman syndrome. It doesn\x{2019}t make sense, on the outside, when a woman-even one who\x{2019}s been victimized for years-kills her husband when he\x{2019}s fast asleep.\x{201d}\x{201c}Objection,\x{201d} Diana said. \x{201c}Does anyone see a battered woman on trial?\x{201d}\x{201c}I\x{2019}ll allow it,\x{201d} Judge Wagner replied.\x{201c}Even when a battered woman is not immediately under physical threat, she psychologically believes she is, thanks to a chronic, escalating pattern of violence that\x{2019}s caused her to suffer from PTSD. It\x{2019}s living in this constant state of fear that something\x{2019}s going to happen, that it\x{2019}s going to keep happening, which leads her to pick up the gun at that moment, even though her husband is snoring. To her, he is still an immediate threat,\x{201d} King said. \x{201c}A child who is suffering from PTSD, like Peter, is terrified that the bully is going to kill him eventually. Even if the bully is not at that moment shoving him into a locker or punching him, it could happen at any second. And so, like the battered wife, he takes action even when-to you and me-nothing seems to warrant the attack.\x{201d}\x{201c}Wouldn\x{2019}t someone notice this sort of irrational fear?\x{201d} Jordan asked.\x{201c}Probably not. A child who suffers from PTSD has made unsuccessful attempts to get help, and as the victimization continues, he stops asking for it. He withdraws socially, because he\x{2019}s never quite sure when interaction is going to lead to another incident of bullying. He probably thinks of killing himself. He escapes into a fantasy world, where he can call the shots. However, he starts retreating there so often that it gets harder and harder to separate that from reality. During the actual incidents of bullying, a child with PTSD might retreat into an altered state of consciousness-a dissociation from reality to keep him from feeling pain or humiliation while the incident occurs. That\x{2019}s exactly what I think happened to Peter on March sixth.\x{201d}\x{201c}Even though none of the kids who\x{2019}d bullied him were present in his bedroom when that email appeared?\x{201d}\x{201c}Correct. Peter had spent his entire life being beaten and taunted and threatened, to the point where he believed he would be killed by those same kids if he didn\x{2019}t do something. The email triggered a dissociative state, and when he went to Sterling High and fired shots, he was completely unaware of what he was doing.\x{201d}\x{201c}How long can a dissociative state last?\x{201d}\x{201c}It depends. Peter could have been dissociating for several hours.\x{201d}\x{201c}Hours?\x{201d} Jordan repeated.\x{201c}Absolutely. There\x{2019}s no point during the shootings that illustrates to me conscious awareness of his actions.\x{201d}Jordan glanced at the prosecutor. \x{201c}We all saw a video where Peter sat down after firing shots in the cafeteria and ate a bowl of cereal. Is that meaningful to your diagnosis?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes. In fact, I can\x{2019}t think of clearer proof that Peter was still dissociating at that moment. You\x{2019}ve got a boy who is completely unaware of the fact that he\x{2019}s surrounded by classmates he\x{2019}d either killed, wounded, or sent fleeing. He sits down and takes the time to calmly pour a bowl of Rice Krispies, unaffected by the carnage around him.\x{201d}\x{201c}What about the fact that many of the children Peter fired at were not part of what could commonly be called the \x{2018}popular crowd\x{2019}? That there were special-needs children and scholars and even a teacher who became his victims?\x{201d}\x{201c}Again,\x{201d} the psychiatrist said, \x{201c}we\x{2019}re not talking about rational behavior. Peter wasn\x{2019}t calculating his actions; at the moment he was shooting, he had separated himself from the reality of the situation. Anyone Peter encountered during those nineteen minutes was a potential threat.\x{201d}\x{201c}In your opinion, when did Peter\x{2019}s dissociative state end?\x{201d} Jordan asked.\x{201c}When Peter was in custody, speaking to Detective Ducharme. That\x{2019}s when he started reacting normally, given the horror of the situation. He began to cry and ask for his mother-which indicates both a recognition of his surroundings and an appropriate, childlike response.\x{201d}Jordan leaned against the rail of the jury box. \x{201c}There\x{2019}s been some evidence in this case, Doctor, that Peter wasn\x{2019}t the only child in the school who was bullied. So why did he react this way to it?\x{201d}\x{201c}Well, as I said, different people have different responses to stress. In Peter\x{2019}s case, I saw an extreme emotional vulnerability, which, in fact, was the reason he was teased. Peter didn\x{2019}t play by the codes of boys. He wasn\x{2019}t a big athlete. He wasn\x{2019}t tough. He was sensitive. And difference is not always respected-particularly when you\x{2019}re a teenager. Adolescence is about fitting in, not standing out.\x{201d}\x{201c}How does a child who is emotionally vulnerable wind up one day carrying four guns into a school and shooting twenty-nine people?\x{201d}\x{201c}Part of it is the PTSD-Peter\x{2019}s response to chronic victimization. But a big part of it, too, is the society that created both Peter and those bullies. Peter\x{2019}s response is one enforced by the world he lives in. He sees violent video games selling off the shelves at stores; he listens to music that glorifies murder and rape. He watches his tormentors shove him, strike him, push him, demean him. He lives in a state, Mr. McAfee, whose license plate reads \x{2018}Live Free or Die.\x{2019}\x{201d} King shook his head. \x{201c}All Peter did, one morning, was turn into the person he\x{2019}d been expected to be all along.\x{201d}Nobody knew this, but once, Josie had broken up with Matt Royston.They had been going out for nearly a year when Matt picked her up one Saturday night. An upperclassman on the football team-someone Brady knew-was having a party at his house. You up for it? Matt had asked, even though he\x{2019}d already been driving there when he asked her.The house had been pulsing like a carnival by the time they arrived, cars parked on the curb and the sidewalk and the lawn. Through the upstairs windows, Josie could see people dancing; as they walked up the driveway, a girl was throwing up in the bushes.Matt didn\x{2019}t let go of her hand. They twined through wall-to-wall bodies, embroidering their path to the kitchen, where the keg was set up, and then back to the dining room, where the table had been tipped on its side to create a bigger dance floor. The kids they passed were not only from Sterling High, but other towns, too. Some had the red-rimmed, loose-jawed stare that came from smoking pot. Guys and girls sniffed at each other, circling for sex.She didn\x{2019}t know anyone, but that wasn\x{2019}t important, because she was with Matt. They pressed closer, in the heat of a hundred other bodies. Matt slid his leg between hers while the music beat like blood, and she lifted up her arms to fit herself against him.Everything had gone wrong when she went to use the bathroom. First, Matt had wanted to follow her-he said it wasn\x{2019}t safe for her to be alone. She finally convinced him it would take all of thirty seconds, but as she started off, a tall boy wearing a Green Day shirt and a hoop earring turned too quickly and spilled his beer on her. Oh, shit, he\x{2019}d said.It\x{2019}s okay. Josie had a tissue in her pocket; she took it out and started to blot her blouse dry.Let me, the boy said, and he took the napkin from her. At the same time they both realized how ridiculous it was trying to soak up that much liquid with a tiny square of Kleenex. He started laughing, and then she did, and his hand was still lightly resting on her shoulder when Matt came up and punched him in the face.What are you doing! Josie had screamed. The boy was out cold on the floor, and other people were trying to get out of the way but stay close enough to see the fight. Matt grabbed her wrist so hard that she thought it was going to snap. He dragged her out of the house and into the car, where she sat in stony silence.He was just trying to help, Josie said.Matt put the car into reverse and lurched backward. You want to stay? You want to be a slut?He\x{2019}d started to drive like a lunatic-running red lights, taking corners on two wheels, doubling the speed limit. She told him to slow down three times, and then she just closed her eyes and hoped it would be over soon.When Matt had screeched to a stop in front of her house, she turned to him, unusually calm. I don\x{2019}t want to go out with you anymore, she had said, and she got out of the car. His voice trailed her to the front door: Good. Why would I want to go out with a fucking whore, anyway?She had managed to slip by her mother, feigning a headache. In the bathroom, she\x{2019}d stared at herself in the mirror, trying to figure out who this girl was who had suddenly grown such a backbone, and why she still felt like crying. She\x{2019}d lain in her bed for an hour, tears leaking from the corners of her eyes, wondering why-if she\x{2019}d been the one to end it-she felt so miserable.When the phone rang <<after three in the morning|9h>>, Josie grabbed it and hung it up again, so that when her mother picked up, she would assume it had been a wrong number. She held her breath for a few seconds, and then lifted the receiver and punched in *69. She knew, even before she saw the familiar string of numbers, that it was Matt.Josie, he had said, when she called back. Were you lying?About what?Loving me?She had pressed her face into the pillow. No, she whispered.I can\x{2019}t live without you, Matt had said, and then she heard something that sounded like a bottle of pills being shaken.Josie had frozen. What are you doing?What do you care?Her mind had started racing. She had her driver\x{2019}s permit, but couldn\x{2019}t take the car out herself, and not after dark. She lived too far away from Matt to run there. Don\x{2019}t move, she said. Just\x{2026}don\x{2019}t do anything.Downstairs in the garage, she\x{2019}d found a bicycle she hadn\x{2019}t ridden since she was in middle school, and she pedaled the four miles to Matt\x{2019}s house. By the time she got there, it had been raining; her hair and her clothes were glued to her skin. The light was still on in Matt\x{2019}s bedroom, which was on the first floor. Josie knocked on the window, and he opened it so that she could crawl inside.On his desk was a bottle of Tylenol and another one, open, of Jim Beam. Josie faced him. Did you-But Matt wrapped his arms around her. He smelled of liquor. You told me not to. I\x{2019}d do anything for you. Then he had pulled back from her. Would you do anything for me?Anything, she vowed.Matt had gathered her into his arms. Tell me you didn\x{2019}t mean it.She felt a cage coming down around her; too late she realized that Matt had her trapped by the heart. And like any unwitting animal that was well and truly caught, Josie could escape only by leaving a piece of herself behind.I\x{2019}m so sorry, Josie had said at least a thousand times that night, because it was all her fault.\x{201c}Dr. Wah,\x{201d} Diana said, \x{201c}how much were you paid for your work on this case?\x{201d}\x{201c}My fee is two thousand dollars per day.\x{201d}\x{201c}Would it be fair to say that one of the most important components of diagnosing the defendant was the time you spent interviewing him?\x{201d}\x{201c}Absolutely.\x{201d}\x{201c}During the course of those ten hours, you were relying on him to be truthful with you in his recollection of events, right?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}You\x{2019}d have no way of knowing if he wasn\x{2019}t being truthful, would you?\x{201d}\x{201c}I\x{2019}ve been doing this for some time, Ms. Leven,\x{201d} the psychiatrist said. \x{201c}I\x{2019}ve interviewed enough people to know when someone\x{2019}s trying to put one over on me.\x{201d}\x{201c}Part of what you use in determining whether or not a teen is putting one over on you is taking a look at the circumstances they\x{2019}re in, correct?\x{201d}\x{201c}Sure.\x{201d}\x{201c}And the circumstances in which you found Peter included being locked up in jail for multiple first-degree murders?\x{201d}\x{201c}That\x{2019}s right.\x{201d}\x{201c}So, basically,\x{201d} Diana said, \x{201c}Peter had a huge incentive to find a way out.\x{201d}\x{201c}Or, Ms. Leven,\x{201d} Dr. Wah countered, \x{201c}you could also say he had nothing left to lose by telling the truth.\x{201d}Diana pressed her lips together; a yes or no answer would have done just fine. \x{201c}You said that part of your diagnosis of PTSD came from the fact that the defendant was attempting to get help, and couldn\x{2019}t. Was this based on information he gave you during your interviews?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes, corroborated by his parents, and some of the teachers who testified for you, Ms. Leven.\x{201d}\x{201c}You also said that part of your diagnosis of PTSD was illustrated by Peter\x{2019}s retreat into a fantasy world, correct?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}And you based that on the computer games that Peter told you about during your interviews?\x{201d}\x{201c}Correct.\x{201d}\x{201c}Isn\x{2019}t it true that when you sent Peter to Dr. Ghertz, you told him he was going to have some brain scans done?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}Couldn\x{2019}t Peter have told Dr. Ghertz that a smiling face looked angry, if he thought it would help you out with a diagnosis?\x{201d}\x{201c}I suppose it would be possible\x{2026}\x{201d}\x{201c}You also said, Doctor, that reading an email the morning of March sixth is what put Peter into a dissociative state, one strong enough to last through Peter\x{2019}s entire killing spree at Sterling High-\x{201d}\x{201c}Objection-\x{201d}\x{201c}Sustained,\x{201d} the judge said.\x{201c}Did you base that conclusion on anything other than what Peter Houghton told you-Peter, who was sitting in a jail cell, charged with ten murders and nineteen attempted murders?\x{201d}King Wah shook his head. \x{201c}No, but any other psychiatrist would have done the same.\x{201d}Diana just raised a brow. \x{201c}Any psychiatrist who stood to make two thousand bucks a day,\x{201d} she said, and even before Jordan objected she withdrew her remark. \x{201c}You said that Peter was suffering from suicide ideation.\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}So he wanted to kill himself?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes. That\x{2019}s very common for patients with PTSD.\x{201d}\x{201c}Detective Ducharme has testified that there were one hundred sixteen bullet casings found in the high school that morning. Another thirty unspent rounds were found on Peter\x{2019}s person, and another fifty-two unspent rounds were found in the backpack he was carrying, along with two guns he didn\x{2019}t use. So, do the math for me, Doctor. How many bullets are we talking about?\x{201d}\x{201c}One hundred and ninety-eight.\x{201d}Diana faced him. \x{201c}In a span of nineteen minutes, Peter had two hundred chances to kill himself, instead of every other student he encountered at Sterling High. Is that right, Doctor?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes. But there is an extremely fine line between a suicide and a homicide. Many depressed people who have made the decision to shoot themselves choose, at the last moment, to shoot someone else instead.\x{201d}Diana frowned. \x{201c}I thought Peter was in a dissociated state,\x{201d} she said. \x{201c}I thought he was incapable of making choices.\x{201d}\x{201c}He was. He was pulling the trigger without any thought of consequence or knowledge of what he was doing.\x{201d}\x{201c}Either that, or it was a tissue-paper line he felt like crossing, right?\x{201d}Jordan stood up. \x{201c}Objection. She\x{2019}s bullying my witness.\x{201d}\x{201c}Oh, for God\x{2019}s sake, Jordan,\x{201d} Diana snapped, \x{201c}you can\x{2019}t use your defense on me.\x{201d}\x{201c}Counselors,\x{201d} the judge warned.\x{201c}You also testified, Doctor, that this dissociative state of Peter\x{2019}s ended when Detective Ducharme began to ask him questions at the police station, correct?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}Would it be fair to say that you based this assumption on the fact that at that moment, Peter started to respond in an appropriate manner, given the situation he was in?\x{201d}\x{201c}Yes.\x{201d}\x{201c}Then how do you explain how, hours earlier, when three officers pointed a gun at Peter and told him to drop his weapon, he was able to do what they asked?\x{201d}Dr. Wah hesitated. \x{201c}Well.\x{201d}\x{201c}Isn\x{2019}t that an appropriate response, when three policemen have their weapons drawn and pointed at you?\x{201d}\x{201c}He put the gun down,\x{201d} the psychiatrist said, \x{201c}because even on a subliminal level, he understood that otherwise, he was going to be shot.\x{201d}\x{201c}But Doctor,\x{201d} Diana said. \x{201c}I thought you told us that Peter wanted to die.\x{201d}She sat back down, satisfied that Jordan could do nothing on redirect that would damage the headway she\x{2019}d made. \x{201c}Dr. Wah,\x{201d} he said, \x{201c}you spent a lot of time with Peter, didn\x{2019}t you?\x{201d}\x{201c}Unlike some doctors in my field,\x{201d} he said pointedly, \x{201c}I actually believe in meeting the client you\x{2019}re going to be talking about in court.\x{201d}\x{201c}Why is this important?\x{201d}\x{201c}To build a rapport,\x{201d} the psychiatrist said. \x{201c}To foster a relationship between doctor and patient.\x{201d}\x{201c}Would you take everything a patient told you at face value?\x{201d}\x{201c}Certainly not, especially under these circumstances.\x{201d}\x{201c}In fact, there are many ways to corroborate a client\x{2019}s story, aren\x{2019}t there?\x{201d}\x{201c}Of course. In Peter\x{2019}s case, I spoke with his parents. There were instances in the school records where bullying was mentioned-although there was no response from the administration. The police package I received supported Peter\x{2019}s statement about his email being sent out to several hundred members of the school community.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did you find any corroborative points that helped you diagnose the dissociative state Peter went into on March sixth?\x{201d} Jordan asked.\x{201c}Yes. Although the police investigation stated that Peter had created a list of target victims, there were far more people shot who were not on the list\x{2026}who were, in fact, students he didn\x{2019}t even know by name.\x{201d}\x{201c}Why is that important?\x{201d}\x{201c}Because it tells me that at the time he was shooting, he wasn\x{2019}t targeting individual students. He was merely going through the motions.\x{201d}\x{201c}Thank you, Doctor,\x{201d} Jordan said, and he nodded to Diana.She looked at the psychiatrist. \x{201c}Peter told you he had been humiliated in the cafeteria,\x{201d} she said. \x{201c}Did he mention any other specific places?\x{201d}\x{201c}The playground. The school bus. The boys\x{2019} bathroom and the locker room.\x{201d}\x{201c}When Peter started shooting at Sterling High, did he go into the principal\x{2019}s office?\x{201d}\x{201c}Not that I\x{2019}m aware of.\x{201d}\x{201c}How about the library?\x{201d}\x{201c}No.\x{201d}\x{201c}The staff lounge?\x{201d}Dr. Wah shook his head. \x{201c}No.\x{201d}\x{201c}The art studio?\x{201d}\x{201c}I don\x{2019}t believe so.\x{201d}\x{201c}In fact, Peter went from the cafeteria, to the bathrooms, to the gym, to the locker room. He went methodically from one venue where he\x{2019}d been bullied to the next, right?\x{201d}\x{201c}It seems so.\x{201d}\x{201c}You said he was going through the motions, Doctor,\x{201d} Diana said. \x{201c}But wouldn\x{2019}t you call that a plan?\x{201d}When Peter got back to the jail that night, the detention officer who took him to his cell handed him a letter. \x{201c}You missed mail call,\x{201d} he said, and Peter couldn\x{2019}t speak, so unaccustomed was he to that concentrated a dose of kindness.He sat down with his back to the wall on the lower bunk and surveyed the envelope. He was a little nervous, now, about mail-he had been since Jordan reamed him for talking to that reporter. But this envelope wasn\x{2019}t typed, like that one had been. This letter was handwritten, with little puffy circles floating over the i\x{2019}s like clouds.He ripped it open and unfolded the letter inside. It smelled like oranges.Dear Peter,You don\x{2019}t know me by name, but I was number 9. That\x{2019}s how I left the school, with a big magic marker label on my forehead. You tried to kill me.I am not at your trial, so don\x{2019}t try to find me in the crowd. I couldn\x{2019}t stand being in that town anymore, so my parents moved a month ago. I start school in a week here in Minnesota, and already people have heard about me. They only know me as a victim from Sterling High. I don\x{2019}t have interests, I don\x{2019}t have a personality, I don\x{2019}t even have a history, except the one you gave me.I had a 4.0 average but I don\x{2019}t care very much about grades anymore. What\x{2019}s the point. I used to have all these dreams, but now I don\x{2019}t know if I\x{2019}ll go to college, since I still can\x{2019}t sleep through the night. I can\x{2019}t deal with people who sneak up behind me either, or doors that slam really loud, or fireworks. I\x{2019}ve been in therapy long enough to tell you one thing: I\x{2019}m never going to set foot in Sterling again.You shot me in the back. The doctors said I was lucky-that if I\x{2019}d sneezed or turned to look at you I would be in a wheelchair now. Instead, I just have to deal with the people who stare when I forget and put on a tank top-anyone can see the scars from the bullet and the chest tubes and the stitches. I don\x{2019}t care-they used to stare at the zits on my face; now they just have another place to focus their attention.I\x{2019}ve thought about you a lot. I think you should go to jail. It\x{2019}s fair, and this wasn\x{2019}t, and there\x{2019}s a kind of balance in that.I was in your French class, did you know that? I sat in the row by the window, second from the back. You always seemed sort of mysterious, and I liked your smile.I would have liked to be your friend.Sincerely,Angela PhlugPeter folded the letter and slipped it inside his pillowcase. Ten minutes later, he took it out again. He read it all night long, over and over, until the sun rose; until he did not need to see the words to recite it by heart.Lacy had dressed for her son. Although it was nearly eighty-five degrees outside, she was wearing a sweater she had dug out of a box in the attic, a pink angora one that Peter had liked to stroke like a kitten when he was tiny. Around her wrist was a bracelet Peter had made her in fourth grade by rolling up tiny bits of magazines into splashy colored beads. She had on a gray patterned skirt that Peter had laughed at once, saying it looked like a computer\x{2019}s